To add the service account to the admin group in the ADSI, 
$port = 3890   # <-- use your AD LDS LDAP port
$domain = "CONTOSO"
$account = "msa_ldap"   # <-- your service account name (no domain)

# Get AD LDS Configuration naming context
$root = [ADSI]"LDAP://localhost:$port/RootDSE"
$cfg  = $root.configurationNamingContext

# Bind to AD LDS Administrators role
$adminsDn = "CN=Administrators,CN=Roles," + $cfg
$admins   = [ADSI]"LDAP://LDAPServer:$port/$adminsDn"

# Translate DOMAIN\account to SID
$nt = New-Object System.Security.Principal.NTAccount($domain,$account)
$sid = $nt.Translate([System.Security.Principal.SecurityIdentifier]).Value

# Add as a Windows principal member of the AD LDS Administrators role
$admins.Properties["member"].Add("<SID=$sid>")
$admins.CommitChanges()

The service can't use the ADLDS port of the ADDS you have to give a different port: 3890 ssl:6360

Check for NTLM restrictions windows server 2003 requires NTLM. The august patch might have restricted this:
Get-itemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Lsa" -Name "LmCompatibilityLevel"

Check smbv1 status adlds often uses the local workstation/server service to talk to DC via smb
Get-WindowsFeature FS-SMB1
 
Check the service-specific error code run this to see exactly why the service stopped
Get-EventLog -LogName System -Source "Service Control Manager" -Newest 10 | Where-Object {$_Meassage -like ADLDS"} | Select-Object -Property EventID, Message | Format-List

